Governorship aspirants on the platform of the Peoples Democratic Party from Abia, Ebonyi, and Enugu states on Thursday participated in a screening exercise at the party’s zonal office in Enugu. The aspirants screened from Abia were Senator Enyinnaya Abaribe; the state deputy governor, Sir Ude Oko Chukwu, Senator Emma Nwaka; Nnanna Nwafor; and Ikpeazu’s preferred successor, Prof. Ekeazer Ikonne. As many as 12 aspirants from Enugu State were screened. They included Senator Ike Ekweremadu, Chijioke Edeoga, Capt. Evarest Nnaji, Chinyeaka Oha, Prof. Bath Nnaji, Peter Mba, Josef-Ken Onoh, Senator Gilbert Nnaji, Gabriel Aja, Prof. Hillary Edeoga, Dan Anike, and Pastor Nwoye. Those screened from Ebonyi included Senator Obinna Ogba, Fidelis Nwankwo, Anayo Nwonu, Sylvester Ogbaga, and Augustine Nwazukwu. Some of the aspirants who spoke to journalists shortly after their screening described the exercise as seamless and hoped they would be cleared. They also expressed support for the proposal of the National Drug Law Enforcement Agency that political parties make drug tests part of the screening requirements for aspirants seeking to contest political offices in the 2023 elections on their platforms. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com